00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:51.000
Yeah.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:55.000
And that's how their lifelong collaboration started.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:57.000
How amazing.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:02.000
So he only died recently, didn't he, I think?

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:03.000
Yeah.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:04.000
Yeah.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:05.000
Yeah.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:15.000
So he was a member of this, is it Severn Estuary levels research committee that you're on?

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:16.000
Yeah.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:26.000
Back in the early to mid 1980s, so we're going back a long way now, there was a proposal

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:29.000
to build a barrage across the Severn Estuary.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:30.000
Have you heard of that?

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:31.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:39.000
Now that would have had huge implications for lots of things, including the archaeology.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:40.000
Yeah.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:47.000
So some of the archaeologists who were working in and around the estuary back in the 1980s

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:54.000
got together to establish what they call the Severn Estuary levels research committee.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:55.000
Okay.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:33:01.000
Now the Severn barrage proposal disappeared relatively quickly.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:02.000
Yeah.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:07.000
Because it basically would be so phenomenally expensive.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:08.000
Yeah.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:10.000
It didn't get going.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:17.000
But I think it did, it stimulated this sort of group of archaeologists to stay together

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:21.000
with this, it's a relatively informal little sort of research group.

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:22.000
Yeah.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:29.000
And so to say, I became a member of it when I started my PhD in 1989.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:30.000
Okay.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:40.000
When my recollection is that the threat of the barrage had largely passed, I think.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:47.000
But I mean, John Allen was very, very active back then studying his salt marshes and he'd

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:51.000
got interested in sort of medieval reclamation and so on.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:52.000
Yeah.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:58.000
Martin had done some work at Breeing Down on the Somerset side of the estuary.

00:33:58.000 --> 00:33:59.000
Yeah.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:04.000
He, I think, was now getting interested on the Welsh side.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:11.000
There was another remarkable figure in the history of the levels, was a chap called Derek

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:12.000
Upton.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:14.000
Yes, yes, I was going to ask you about him.

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:15.000
Yeah.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:20.000
He worked at the steelworks and he was a bird watcher.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:23.000
And he's somebody else with the most amazing eye.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:26.000
He started seeing strange things.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:27.000
Yeah.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:31.000
Seeing objects, seeing things in the intertidal area of the estuary.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:32.000
Yeah.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:38.000
I don't know who he first reported his finds to.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:39.000
I'm not sure.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:40.000
Yeah.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:45.000
But once again, quite quickly, he got to know various archaeologists and people that he

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:47.000
could report his finds to.

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:48.000
Yeah.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.000
And took him seriously as well, I suppose.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:51.000
Sorry?

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:53.000
And also who took him seriously.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:54.000
Absolutely.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:55.000
I think that was the key thing.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:56.000
Yeah.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:03.000
So he was spotting little woven fish baskets and so on.

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:04.000
Yeah.

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:09.000
I think he might have discovered some of the first human footprints.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:10.000
Yes.

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:14.000
Of course, Martin Bell has spent a lot of his time studying human footprints.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:15.000
Yeah.

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:16.000
And so on.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:19.000
So there was this sort of, it's just very fortuitous.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:28.000
I think a lot of people sort of being around the estuary and then suddenly being drawn

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.000
in by this particular threat.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:31.000
Yeah.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:32.000
Yeah.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:39.000
And then kind of sticking together once that threat had gone, simply because it's a remarkable

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.000
landscape to research.

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:44.000
And it's raised its profile, I suppose, as well.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:45.000
Yeah.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:48.000
So does it have any statutory protection?

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:51.000
It does for its nature conservation interests.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:52.000
Yeah.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:36:01.000
I mean, both sides of the estuary are relatively well protected in terms of habitat, ecology

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:03.000
related protection.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:10.000
But unfortunately, there's not really anything big and powerful on the statutory front that

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:14.000
protects it from solar farms, et cetera.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:15.000
Yeah.

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:22.000
So no, my feeling is that our special landscapes don't have enough legal protection.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:23.000
Yeah.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:26.000
And we're seeing this on the grant levels.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:29.000
They're not going to be there in a few years' time.

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:30.000
Do you not think so?

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:31.000
Really?

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:32.000
Well, no.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:35.000
I mean, they're building a solar farm at Whitsun.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:36.000
Are they really?

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
I didn't know that.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.000
Yeah, that's going ahead.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:41.000
Why?

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:44.000
There's posals for a huge one on the Wentlewg level.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:46.000
Yeah, yeah, I've heard that one.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:47.000
Yeah.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:51.000
And there's proposals for another one at Redwick.

00:36:51.000 --> 00:37:00.000
And although solar farms don't permanently destroy a landscape, like housing development

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:05.000
or steelworks, for example, but they'll ruin the appearance.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:07.000
No, there's no doubt about it.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:08.000
Yeah.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:19.000
And on the Gloucestershire side, once again, when you drive along the M4 from South Wales

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:25.000
to Bristol, you go over an equivalent wetland on the Bristol side of the estuary.

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:30.000
And it's just getting covered in massive industrial units.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:33.000
I think there's a huge Amazon depot there, for example.

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:34.000
Oh, wow.

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:36.000
Well, I suppose it's happened in Whendlewg already, hasn't it?

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:41.000
You know, that has been subject to far more development than the Caldecott side.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:42.000
Yeah.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:50.000
But for you, I mean, has wetlands become your specialism, would you say?

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:56.000
Well, it was for, once again, probably sort of 10, 15 years or so.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:37:57.000
Yeah.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:01.000
I mean, I made a conscious decision to move on.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:02.000
Yes.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:10.000
Simply because as an academic, it's very easy to almost get typecast, to use an acting analogy.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:12.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:18.000
So I absolutely consciously decided, right, I'm now going to start studying other things.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:19.000
Yeah.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:23.000
So I do quite a lot of work now.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:29.000
Well, I had a period in my life, a bit like John Allen said, you should spend 10 years on something and then move on.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:37.000
I had a period when I did a lot of work on regional variation in landscape character.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:40.000
So why is the Devon landscape so different to Northamptonshire?

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:41.000
OK.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:42.000
And so.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:43.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:48.000
Then I got very interested in what happened when Britain ceased to be part of the Roman Empire

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:54.000
and whether that was actually a really significant change or not.

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:57.000
So I had quite a, I had about 10 years studying that.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:00.000
So the Dark Ages, you mean?

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:03.000
Yeah, the start of what are traditionally called the Dark Ages.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:10.000
I think a lot of us would suggest they weren't quite as dark as they used to be.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:18.000
But yeah, what is traditionally seen as being the sort of almost like the end of civilisation in the Roman period.

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:30.000
But actually, I think my work hopefully shows that if you were just like a peasant farmer ploughing a few fields and tending a few sheep, not a lot actually changed.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:35.000
So I spent a few years sort of studying that.

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:47.000
So I sort of I tried to move on from wetlands, not because I didn't enjoy studying them, but just because, you know, a typical academic career is about 40 years.

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:52.000
And I don't think many academics want to spend 40 years studying exactly the same thing.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:55.000
A change is always good, isn't it, I think?

00:39:55.000 --> 00:40:08.000
Yeah, but one of the reasons why I've so enjoyed my involvement in the Living Levels project is that it has brought me back to a landscape that I studied so intensively for two years.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:10.000
For two years, that was my whole life.

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:11.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:20.000
And I've done I do periodically return to some of these wetland landscapes just to do a little bit of work on something that I'm interested in.

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:21.000
Yeah.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:27.000
I asked before actually about how much if your work is reliant on aerial views.

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:30.000
Do you have to rely? Is that part of it for you?

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:34.000
A bit.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:41.000
The bread and butter is looking at maps because they are available in such detail.

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:44.000
So what age do you go back to?

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:49.000
Well, there's good map coverage for the whole country from the 19th century.

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:50.000
Yeah.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:58.000
So sort of middle of the 19th century, there's really detailed maps of pretty much the whole country.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:40:59.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:05.000
But some areas there are some earlier maps as well.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:06.000
OK, yeah.

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:09.000
The maps are earlier than aerial photographs.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:17.000
And also aerial photographs, the earliest aerial photographs really from the 1940s.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:18.000
OK, yeah.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:19.000
But they're pretty fuzzy.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:29.000
But there are there are places where, for example, earthworks, sort of humps and bumps,

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:36.000
they are they show up on aerial photographs from, say, the late 1940s.

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:40.000
But those earthworks now have been completely ploughed flat.

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:41.000
Yeah.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:48.000
So so yeah, I think to understand the landscape, you've really got to look at absolutely everything you've got at your disposal.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:49.000
Yeah.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:54.000
Although I would say it's the maps that are the starting point.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:55.000
Yeah.

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:58.000
I mean, maps tell a story all on their own, don't they?

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.000
I mean, I love a map.

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:07.000
Do you use the oh, gosh, my name's gone, the the internal drainage board maps.

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.000
How far back do they go?

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:10.000
Yeah.

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:12.000
Yeah.

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:22.000
I mean, the the earliest of the maps that show individual fields and buildings and so on are 1830 to 1831.

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:30.000
And those were the earliest maps that cover the whole of the grant levels.

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:34.000
And they are an absolutely remarkable source.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:35.000
Are they?

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:42.000
So I mean, they were really the starting point of the mapping in my grant levels, historic landscape study.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:43.000
Really?

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:51.000
Has there been a high point for you or, you know, punching the air moment for you in all your work down there?

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:53.000
On the levels?

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:54.000
Yeah.

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:58.000
I don't know, really.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:11.000
Off the top of my head, I don't think I can.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:16.000
I mean, I've had various very memorable moments.

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:17.000
Yeah.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:21.000
But I don't think there is quite one punching the air.

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:29.000
I mean, I do remember doing a survey of the intertidal area at Magor Pill.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:30.000
Yeah.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:34.000
With John Allen in February.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:35.000
Oh, God.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:39.000
And it was bitterly cold.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:50.000
And that absolutely tested my commitment to archaeology.

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:52.000
Cold and wet.

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:58.000
Yeah, it was that was awful from the conditions, but it was just fascinating.

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:00.000
You know, spending a week with the great man.

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:01.000
Yeah.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.000
So interpreting all of this archaeology.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:10.000
So I mean, that was that was a definite sort of highlight.

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:15.000
But yes, I haven't really got the air punching moment.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:18.000
I should probably think of something when we sign off.

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:20.000
Yeah.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:28.000
What about, I'm not sure this is a silly question or not, but the work you do,

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:34.000
is it something that can be used by?

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:45.000
Let me think I don't ask this question as a way of informing the future.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:48.000
Because that is what the great levels historic landscape study.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:52.000
I mean, that was all about.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:59.000
And it did it fade through to another Caddo Countryside Council for Wales

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:04.000
initiative, which was to produce a register of historic landscapes in Wales.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:05.000
Yeah.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:16.000
And it identified 60 ish landscapes of particular historic importance in Wales,

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:19.000
one of which is the Gwent levels.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:24.000
And so the Gwent levels was the first one of the landscapes in the register to see

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:30.000
this sort of really intensive study.

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:34.000
So yeah, I think that study really did sort of have an impact in terms of raising

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:43.000
the profile of the concept of how important still used landscapes are and the

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:46.000
time depth that they have.

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:52.000
And there was similar work that was done in England as well.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:59.000
And it was a very exciting period to be sort of working in what at that time was a

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:03.000
really new and a really sort of innovative concept.

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:08.000
The archaeologists shouldn't just be grubbing about in the dirt, but archaeologists

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:14.000
should be appreciating the historic importance of the landscape all around us.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:17.000
I think it's something that we take for granted now.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:25.000
But thinking back to that sort of early mid 1990s, very few archaeologists had any

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:34.000
interest at all in the historic age of fields that they walk through or roads that

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:35.000
they drive down.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:38.000
They were just roads and fields.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:44.000
They are actually often as old, if not older, than things that archaeologists grub

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:45.000
around in the dirt.

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:47.000
It's so interesting.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:50.000
Because like you said earlier, it's so relatable, isn't it?

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:52.000
It's so relatable.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:47:00.000
What about have you had to, so you said you've used maps and old documents, Doomsday

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:01.000
Book.

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:08.000
Have you ever used spoken to locals and asked for their folk memory maybe?

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:14.000
Well, this is something that I wish I'd done more of in the Great Neville's Historic

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:15.000
Landscape Study.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:17.000
I did talk to Neville Walters.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:18.000
Oh, wow.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:19.000
He's brilliant.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:20.000
Have you spoken to him?

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:23.000
I've got one of my best interviews.

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:29.000
There was a lady who worked for the Countryside Council for Wales.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:38.000
I think her name was Susan Howard, who was my first point of contact at the Countryside

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:42.000
Council for Wales, just as Rick Turner was my first point of contact in Caddick.

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:48.000
She introduced me to various sort of local people.

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:52.000
But Neville was the one who I remember I spent quite a bit of time with.

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:54.000
I spent about half a day with him.

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:57.000
He drove me around various places.

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:06.000
We talked about some of the traditional methods of managing that landscape that he could remember.

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:17.000
I remember he told me he was paid something like sixpence for digging a certain length

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:22.000
of gripe, these spade dug gullies in the surface of the fields.

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:27.000
It was something like sixpence for 30 feet a day or something like that.

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:30.000
That is in that book somewhere.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:32.000
I did write that down.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:42.000
What was really nice was we had a big Living Levels event at the, is it called the Lyset Institute?

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:43.000
Yes, yes.

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:50.000
I was sitting at one of the tables and this elderly gentleman sort of walked past and

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:54.000
sort of looked at me in that sort of knowing way.

00:48:54.000 --> 00:49:02.000
I didn't recognise him because this was about 23, 25 years ago.

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:05.000
He obviously recognised me.

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:09.000
Whether he'd asked somebody, is that Stephen Rippon, I don't know.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:14.000
He obviously recognised me and I recognised that he clearly knew me.

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:17.000
I guessed it might have been him.

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:20.000
I went out and we had a nice little chat.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:27.000
I wish I'd done more of that.

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:33.000
The people I did talk to, it was very useful.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:40.000
I found out about the cycle of cleaning out the ditches.

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:45.000
It's only the major water courses that you would have cleaned out every year.

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:53.000
Then you'd have this cycle of cleaning the minor reams perhaps every three years.

00:49:53.000 --> 00:50:00.000
The field boundaries, a farmer might just clean out two field boundaries a year.

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:04.000
They might have something like almost a 30-year cycle, some of them.

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:11.000
Of course, that's how you get the difference in vegetation in these ditches because you get these different times.

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:14.000
Neville told me all about that.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:23.000
